sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K2040121
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: KillerRed was inserted between the gpdA promoter and trpC terminator on vector pBARGPE1.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chilam Poon
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: KillerRed can be replaced by KillerRed-NLS so that KillerRed can be localized in the nucleus.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K2040120
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The phototoxic protein KillerRed(BBa_K1184000) was placed upstream the fungal terminator TtrpC(BBa_K1021008). Different kinds of fungal promoters with RBS can be added before this composite part to construct protein generators.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chilam Poon
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: KillerRed was from BBa_K1184000. TtrpC was isolated from fungal transformation vector pBARGPE1.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1184000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
KillerRed is a red fluorescent protein that produces reactive oxygen species (ROS) in the presence of yellow-orange light (540-585 nm). KillerRed is engineered from Aequorea victoria GFP (avGFP) to be phototoxic. It has been shown that KillerRed produces superoxide radical anions by reacting with water. Superoxide reacts with the chromophore of KillerRed, causing it to become dark, which ultimately gives rise to a bleaching effect. KillerRed is spectrally similar to mRFP1 with a similar brightness. KillerRed is oligomeric and may form large aggregates.
This sequence is codon optimized for mammalian cells and has 14 rare proline codons for E. coli (CCC) and one rare arginine codon (AGA). Codon optimization should be taken into consideration if large amounts of the protein are required. Expression on a high-copy plasmid has produced detectable fluorescent signal, however.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Eric Pederson
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Engineered from avGFP. Provided by the Bruchez lab at Carnegie Mellon
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This sequence is not codon optimized for E. coli.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1021010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The strong constitutive promoter used to regulate the glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase gene in Aspergillus nidulans.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Swati Sureka
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: It was taken from pBARGPE1 from the Fungal Genetics Stock Center.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The vector was unsequenced so we carried out several rounds of sequencing to determine the promoter sequence in order to be able to BioBrick it.
